</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">As digital breast tomosynthesis (DBT) becomes widely used, radiologists must understand the basic principles of <i>(a)</i> image acquisition, <i>(b)</i> artifacts, and <i>(c)</i> quality control (QC) that are specific to DBT. Standard acquisition parameters common to both full-field digital mammography (FFDM) and DBT are combinations of x-ray tube voltage, current exposure time, and anode target and filter combinations. Image acquisition parameters specific to DBT include tube motion, sweep angle, and number of projections. Continuous tube motion or x-ray emission decreases imaging time but leads to focal spot blurring when compared with step-and-shoot techniques. The sweep angle and number of projections determines resolution. Wider sweep angles allow greater out-of-plane (z-axis) resolution, improving visualization of masses and architecture distortion. A greater number of projections increases in-plane or x-y axis resolution, improving visualization of microcalcifications. Artifacts related to DBT include blurring-ripple, truncation, and loss of skin and superficial tissue resolution. Motion artifacts are difficult to recognize because of inherent out-of-plane blurring. To maintain optimal image quality and an “as low as reasonably achievable” (ALARA) radiation dose, regular QC must be performed. DBT is considered a new imaging modality; therefore, breast imaging facilities are required to obtain a separate certification in addition to that in FFDM, and all personnel (radiologists, technologists, and medical physicists) are mandated to complete initial DBT training and maintain appropriate continuing medical education credits.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2019</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180046">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2019180046">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig1a.jpeg" height="1540" width="1255" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Amorphous microcalcifications in a 55-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral spot magnification view shows that the amorphous microcalcifications are difficult to see. <b>(b, c)</b> Two-dimensional synthesized mammogram <b>(b)</b> and DBT image <b>(c)</b> acquired with the use of a high-pass filter show improved visibility of microcalcifications.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig1b.jpeg" height="1540" width="1268" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Amorphous microcalcifications in a 55-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral spot magnification view shows that the amorphous microcalcifications are difficult to see. <b>(b, c)</b> Two-dimensional synthesized mammogram <b>(b)</b> and DBT image <b>(c)</b> acquired with the use of a high-pass filter show improved visibility of microcalcifications.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig1c.jpeg" height="1540" width="1174" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Amorphous microcalcifications in a 55-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral spot magnification view shows that the amorphous microcalcifications are difficult to see. <b>(b, c)</b> Two-dimensional synthesized mammogram <b>(b)</b> and DBT image <b>(c)</b> acquired with the use of a high-pass filter show improved visibility of microcalcifications.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig2a.jpeg" height="1393" width="1245" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Amorphous microcalcifications in a 43-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Two-dimensional synthesized mammogram shows a group of round and amorphous calcifications in the right breast. <b>(b, c)</b> DBT image <b>(b)</b> and FFDM spot magnification view <b>(c)</b> show two microcalcifications (oval). These findings are 2D synthesized mammography–related pseudocalcification artifacts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig2b.jpeg" height="1393" width="1223" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Amorphous microcalcifications in a 43-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Two-dimensional synthesized mammogram shows a group of round and amorphous calcifications in the right breast. <b>(b, c)</b> DBT image <b>(b)</b> and FFDM spot magnification view <b>(c)</b> show two microcalcifications (oval). These findings are 2D synthesized mammography–related pseudocalcification artifacts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig2c.jpeg" height="1393" width="1235" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Amorphous microcalcifications in a 43-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Two-dimensional synthesized mammogram shows a group of round and amorphous calcifications in the right breast. <b>(b, c)</b> DBT image <b>(b)</b> and FFDM spot magnification view <b>(c)</b> show two microcalcifications (oval). These findings are 2D synthesized mammography–related pseudocalcification artifacts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig3a.jpeg" height="876" width="1320" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Blurring-ripple artifact in a 67-year-old woman. Right craniocaudal images obtained in combination DBT <b>(a)</b> and FFDM <b>(b)</b> mode show a falsely thick skin line from blurring of the skin in the DBT image (red arrows in <b>a</b>) and blurring-ripple artifacts associated with coarse calcifications (yellow arrow in <b>a</b>). Both artifacts appear less prominent with FFDM.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig3b.jpeg" height="876" width="1323" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Blurring-ripple artifact in a 67-year-old woman. Right craniocaudal images obtained in combination DBT <b>(a)</b> and FFDM <b>(b)</b> mode show a falsely thick skin line from blurring of the skin in the DBT image (red arrows in <b>a</b>) and blurring-ripple artifacts associated with coarse calcifications (yellow arrow in <b>a</b>). Both artifacts appear less prominent with FFDM.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig4a.jpeg" height="1135" width="1174" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Blurring-ripple artifact from a metallic biopsy clip in a 52-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Synthesized mammogram or C-view mediolateral oblique view of the left breast shows a streak artifact along the sweep direction. <b>(b)</b> DBT section 17 of 63 shows a blurring artifact, with a widening and an indistinct margin. <b>(c)</b> DBT section 40 of 63 shows increased separation of the artifact from blurring into a ripple or “slinky” artifact.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig4b.jpeg" height="1135" width="1354" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Blurring-ripple artifact from a metallic biopsy clip in a 52-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Synthesized mammogram or C-view mediolateral oblique view of the left breast shows a streak artifact along the sweep direction. <b>(b)</b> DBT section 17 of 63 shows a blurring artifact, with a widening and an indistinct margin. <b>(c)</b> DBT section 40 of 63 shows increased separation of the artifact from blurring into a ripple or “slinky” artifact.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig4c.jpeg" height="1125" width="1173" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Blurring-ripple artifact from a metallic biopsy clip in a 52-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Synthesized mammogram or C-view mediolateral oblique view of the left breast shows a streak artifact along the sweep direction. <b>(b)</b> DBT section 17 of 63 shows a blurring artifact, with a widening and an indistinct margin. <b>(c)</b> DBT section 40 of 63 shows increased separation of the artifact from blurring into a ripple or “slinky” artifact.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig5a.jpeg" height="1512" width="1336" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Reduction of blurring-ripple artifact in a 55-year-old woman (same patient as in <a href="#fig1a">Figure 1</a>). Postprocessing metal reduction software can be applied after image acquisition to reduce blurring-ripple artifacts. <b>(a)</b> Synthesized mammogram shows a decrease in streak artifacts. <b>(b)</b> DBT section 10 of 63 also shows substantial reduction of blurring-ripple artifacts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig5b.jpeg" height="1512" width="1314" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Reduction of blurring-ripple artifact in a 55-year-old woman (same patient as in <a href="#fig1a">Figure 1</a>). Postprocessing metal reduction software can be applied after image acquisition to reduce blurring-ripple artifacts. <b>(a)</b> Synthesized mammogram shows a decrease in streak artifacts. <b>(b)</b> DBT section 10 of 63 also shows substantial reduction of blurring-ripple artifacts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig6.jpeg" height="1910" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Dark streak or halo artifacts in a 61-year-old woman. Magnified synthesized mammogram shows dark streak or halo artifacts surrounding surgical clips. The artifacts are the results of photon starvation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig7.jpeg" height="1854" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Simplified diagram of DBT acquisition shows how truncation artifacts occur. The orange area of the breast is not included in the wide projection field of view but contributes to image reconstruction, resulting in a bright-edge artifact. The red area of the breast is located outside the reconstructed volume (indicated by the solid black lines between the compression paddle and the detector) but contributes to attenuation, resulting in stair-step artifacts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig8a.jpeg" height="2116" width="1124" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Stair-step artifact in a 47-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> The shoulder falls outside of the field of view of the reconstructed volume image but appears as a stair-step artifact on a DBT image <b>(a)</b> and as a bright line on a synthesized mammogram (arrows) <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c)</b> The overlying shoulder can be seen on a cine source image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig8b.jpeg" height="2113" width="1154" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Stair-step artifact in a 47-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> The shoulder falls outside of the field of view of the reconstructed volume image but appears as a stair-step artifact on a DBT image <b>(a)</b> and as a bright line on a synthesized mammogram (arrows) <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c)</b> The overlying shoulder can be seen on a cine source image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig8c.jpeg" height="2116" width="1038" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Stair-step artifact in a 47-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> The shoulder falls outside of the field of view of the reconstructed volume image but appears as a stair-step artifact on a DBT image <b>(a)</b> and as a bright line on a synthesized mammogram (arrows) <b>(b)</b>. <b>(c)</b> The overlying shoulder can be seen on a cine source image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig9.jpeg" height="1820" width="1300" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Bright-edge artifact in a 49-year-old woman. Bright-edge artifact manifests as falsely increased attenuation in the axilla.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig10a.jpeg" height="1964" width="743" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Artifacts in a 63-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Spot compression DBT image of the right breast shows a jagged appearance of the skin and loss of detail in the dermal and subcutaneous tissues, secondary to saturation of the detector from a subpectoral dense silicone implant in the field of view. A stair-step artifact from the compression paddle and a blur artifact associated with the biopsy clip are seen. Ripple artifacts are not seen because metal reduction software was applied. <b>(b)</b> Synthesized mammogram shows the same artifacts as on the DBT image (a combination-mode sequence was not performed). <b>(c)</b> Mediolateral oblique nonimplant-displaced FFDM view does not show the artifacts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig10b.jpeg" height="1964" width="611" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Artifacts in a 63-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Spot compression DBT image of the right breast shows a jagged appearance of the skin and loss of detail in the dermal and subcutaneous tissues, secondary to saturation of the detector from a subpectoral dense silicone implant in the field of view. A stair-step artifact from the compression paddle and a blur artifact associated with the biopsy clip are seen. Ripple artifacts are not seen because metal reduction software was applied. <b>(b)</b> Synthesized mammogram shows the same artifacts as on the DBT image (a combination-mode sequence was not performed). <b>(c)</b> Mediolateral oblique nonimplant-displaced FFDM view does not show the artifacts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig10c.jpeg" height="1964" width="863" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. Artifacts in a 63-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Spot compression DBT image of the right breast shows a jagged appearance of the skin and loss of detail in the dermal and subcutaneous tissues, secondary to saturation of the detector from a subpectoral dense silicone implant in the field of view. A stair-step artifact from the compression paddle and a blur artifact associated with the biopsy clip are seen. Ripple artifacts are not seen because metal reduction software was applied. <b>(b)</b> Synthesized mammogram shows the same artifacts as on the DBT image (a combination-mode sequence was not performed). <b>(c)</b> Mediolateral oblique nonimplant-displaced FFDM view does not show the artifacts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig11a.jpeg" height="2256" width="1177" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Combination DBT/FFDM views of the right breast show a motion artifact with blurring at FFDM <b>(a)</b> that is not visible on the synthesized mammogram <b>(b)</b>. Patient motion was related to increased examination time for the double exposure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig11b.jpeg" height="2255" width="1072" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Combination DBT/FFDM views of the right breast show a motion artifact with blurring at FFDM <b>(a)</b> that is not visible on the synthesized mammogram <b>(b)</b>. Patient motion was related to increased examination time for the double exposure.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig12.jpeg" height="1691" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Small ACR mammography accreditation phantom. This phantom is made from acrylic and contains a wax insert to simulate a 4.2-cm compressed breast with 50% adipose and 50% glandular tissue. The wax insert contains three groups of objects: six nylon fibers, five microcalcification groups, and five masses embedded at different depths, resulting in different focal points. DBT sections in which each finding is completely in focus should be used to evaluate for image quality.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig13.jpeg" height="1648" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Line bar phantom. Spatial resolution testing is performed with a line bar phantom placed at 45° to the x-ray tube anode-cathode axis, on top of a 4-cm homogeneous acrylic block. There is greater than three line pairs per millimeter resolution in this DBT image, which is a passing score for Hologic Selenia Dimensions.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig14.jpeg" height="2110" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Image obtained at 0° projection with a Hologic Selenia geometry calibration. The software automatically evaluates whether the embedded beads appear in a predetermined location on the detector.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2019180046/asset/images/large/rg.2019180046.fig15.jpeg" height="1725" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Image from Hologic Selenia flat-field testing performed with a 4-cm radiolucent acrylic block without a compression paddle. A homogeneously dark screen indicates acceptable uniformity with no artifact.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2019180046&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Feig SA. Invited Commentary: digital breast tomosynthesis—the road ahead. <em>RadioGraphics</em> 2014;34(4):e103–e105.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.344140140">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25019449/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Invited+Commentary%3A+digital+breast+tomosynthesis%E2%80%94the+road+ahead&amp;author=SA+Feig&amp;publication_year=2014&amp;journal=RadioGraphi